When I reached the Heights, I explained
that I had come to see everything carried on
decently, and Joseph, who appeared in sum-
cient distress, expressed satisfaction at my pre-
sence. Mr. Heathcliff said he did not perceive
that I was wanted,'but I might stay and order
the arrangements for the funeral, if I chose.

“ Correctly,”he remarked, “ that fool’s body
should be buried at the cross-roads, without
ceremony of any kind—I happened to leave
him ten minutes, yesterday afternoon; and,
in that interval, he fastened the two doors of
the house against me, and he has spent the
night in drinking himself to death deliberately !
\Ve broke in this morning, for we heard him
snorting like a horse; and there he was, laid

